T1  - A Comparative Study of the Satisfaction of American and Mexican Operations
AU  - Slocum, John W.
Y1  - 1971/03/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254713
DO  - 10.5465/254713
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 89
EP  - 97
VL  - 14
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study compared the perceptions of need satisfaction and importance for blue-collar workers in the USA and Mexico. Organizational and technological differences were controlled to isolate culture as the independent variable. Porter's need questionnaire was used to tap employees' attitudes. The data indicate that there were significant differences in nearly every need item score between the two countries. Mexican workers were more satisfied than their counterparts in the USA.
AB  - This study compared the perceptions of need satisfaction and importance for blue-collar workers in the USA and Mexico. Organizational and technological differences were controlled to isolate culture as the independent variable. Porter's need questionnaire was used to tap employees' attitudes. The data indicate that there were significant differences in nearly every need item score between the two countries. Mexican workers were more satisfied than their counterparts in the USA.
